1
00:00:04,467 --> 00:00:13,137
It is interesting to note 
when you deal with, let’s say, art.

2
00:00:13,142 --> 00:00:18,122
They are called ‘recording artists’, 
and there’s other type of artists.

3
00:00:18,462 --> 00:00:23,165
[Art Without Ego]

4
00:00:23,305 --> 00:00:30,075
When someone is supposed 
to be really purely inspired

5
00:00:30,157 --> 00:00:33,987
most often 
they will describe the experience

6
00:00:33,989 --> 00:00:39,479
as if something came down 
and used them as an instrument for expression.

7
00:00:39,479 --> 00:00:41,512
“I don’t know 
where that came from.

8
00:00:41,512 --> 00:00:45,922
Just it all came to me in a flash
all of a sudden.”

9
00:00:45,941 --> 00:00:50,546
Or critics of art, they will say, 
“We see in this artwork—

10
00:00:50,546 --> 00:00:53,856
there is no trace of ego.”

11
00:00:53,856 --> 00:00:57,326
The artists themselves 
may have had a very big ego.

12
00:00:57,326 --> 00:01:00,671
We read books. 
People were shocked to find out.

13
00:01:00,674 --> 00:01:03,412
They are like study ‘10 great artists’,

14
00:01:03,412 --> 00:01:06,922
and they will say,
“This guy was a total jerk.

15
00:01:06,982 --> 00:01:11,382
He had a huge ego. 
He was mean to people.”

16
00:01:11,382 --> 00:01:12,915
And people 
[demonstrating astonishment]

17
00:01:12,915 --> 00:01:15,675
But he produced such beautiful artwork.

18
00:01:15,711 --> 00:01:20,383
What they mean, by application, is: 
those moments were inspired

19
00:01:20,383 --> 00:01:25,011
as if some higher power 
came down

20
00:01:25,011 --> 00:01:30,451
and used this person 
as an instrument for expression.

21
00:01:30,451 --> 00:01:37,042
They’ll start using adjectives or words,

22
00:01:37,042 --> 00:01:42,439
that’s saying like, “It was divine”
or “Almost divine.”

23
00:01:42,439 --> 00:01:46,239
Like they don’t want to give you the impression 
that they believe in God.

24
00:01:46,239 --> 00:01:47,522
So they’ll say,
“It was like that.”

25
00:01:47,522 --> 00:01:49,809
What people describe 
about spiritual experience?
 

26
00:01:49,809 --> 00:01:53,979
“It was like that.”
[Laughing]

27
00:01:53,979 --> 00:02:00,422
But if an artist and hero 
are speaking in a generous sense,

28
00:02:00,422 --> 00:02:05,153
if someone who is an artist
can speak of being inspired

29
00:02:05,153 --> 00:02:09,383
and offering themselves 
as an instrument for revelation,

30
00:02:09,400 --> 00:02:13,870
then why not spiritually speaking?

31
00:02:14,030 --> 00:02:21,070
The only question will be … 
In principle we can’t object to the method,

32
00:02:21,224 --> 00:02:24,174
the delivery mechanism.

33
00:02:24,218 --> 00:02:31,290
All we can really question is: 
whether or not it’s real.

34
00:02:31,290 --> 00:02:35,470
The method of delivery 
is irrelevant here.

35
00:02:35,536 --> 00:02:39,406
What our interest will be 
is: is it real?

36
00:02:39,437 --> 00:02:42,094
Does it really have a touch 
of the divine?

37
00:02:42,094 --> 00:02:48,394
Is it really under divine influence 
or is it something else?

38
00:02:48,394 --> 00:02:55,204
We don’t need to argue 
about how it came.

39
00:02:55,204 --> 00:02:57,283
What substance is there?

40
00:02:57,283 --> 00:03:01,267
Is it really 
divine descended substance

41
00:03:01,267 --> 00:03:04,147
or is it something else?

42
00:03:04,147 --> 00:03:08,457
And to make that 
judgement or assessment

43
00:03:08,457 --> 00:03:13,327
then we’ll have to take 
these things seriously

44
00:03:13,327 --> 00:03:18,098
and study them carefully 
under the guidance of experts.

